{# ── DEFINITION · "speak to an accountant," honestly (prose). FROZEN speakable anchor
   #acct-speak-in-brief-text preserved on the lead paragraph. (H2: "Speak to an accountant," honestly.) ── #}
<section class="sec reveal" id="acct-speak-definition" style="background:var(--color-paper-warm);border-top:1px solid var(--border-subtle);border-bottom:1px solid var(--border-subtle);">
  <div class="ct read read--doc">
    <div class="idx"><span class="idx__n">&sect;01</span><span class="idx__t">In plain terms</span><span class="idx__rule"></span></div>
    <h2 class="h2" style="margin-bottom:18px;">&ldquo;Speak to an accountant,&rdquo; honestly.</h2>
    <div class="prose">
      <p id="acct-speak-in-brief-text">When people search &ldquo;speak to an accountant,&rdquo; they usually mean one of two very different things &mdash; and the honest answer matters. Sometimes they need <em>bookkeeping</em>: someone to clean up the books, set up or fix QuickBooks, reconcile the accounts, produce financial statements they can trust, and advise on what the numbers mean. Other times they need <em>tax</em>: a return prepared and signed, tax advice they can rely on, or someone to deal with the IRS. The word &ldquo;accountant&rdquo; gets used for both, but the credentials are not the same.</p>
      <p>Our team are <strong>Certified QuickBooks ProAdvisors</strong>. That is the first group of work &mdash; the operational accounting inside your books &mdash; and it&rsquo;s what we do well. We are <strong>not CPAs</strong>, so we do not prepare tax returns, give tax advice, or represent anyone before the IRS; that is licensed CPA or enrolled-agent work. We won&rsquo;t blur that line. If your call turns out to be a tax question, the most useful thing we can do is say so clearly and help you coordinate a CPA &mdash; usually with a clean, year-end-ready file already in hand.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

